Pages 162 through 179 in the annotated slide deck cover Thrift.

I used thrift-0.8.0: http://thrift.apache.org/download/

The Java classes generated by Thrift depend the Simple Logging Facade for Java (SLF4J), which you can download from here: http://www.slf4j.org/download.html
You will need slf4j-api-1.6.6.jar and slf4j-simple-1.6.6.jar

To generate plumbing for server/client communication based on the scala_utils.thrift Interface Definition Language (IDL) file:

thrift --gen java --gen py


To compile the generated Java classes:

javac gen-java/scala_utils_plumbing/ScalaUtilsService.java -classpath '/Users/AOK/libthrift-0.8.0.jar:/Users/AOK/slf4j-api-1.6.6.jar:/Users/AOK/slf4j-simple-1.6.6.jar'


To compile ScalaUtilsServer.scala:

scalac  -cp .:gen-java:/Users/AOK/libthrift-0.8.0.jar:/Users/AOK/slf4j-api-1.6.6.jar:/Users/AOK/slf4j-simple-1.6.6.jar ScalaUtilsServer.scala


To run ScalaUtilsServer:

scala  -cp .:gen-java:/Users/AOK/libthrift-0.8.0.jar:/Users/AOK/slf4j-api-1.6.6.jar:/Users/AOK/slf4j-simple-1.6.6.jar ScalaUtilsServer


Running the Python client should yield 2 as follows:

> python PythonClient.py 
2